{
  "verdict": "reject",
  "conceptual_groups": [
    {
      "id": "group-1",
      "summary": "The authority model is anchored to static documents in a way that blurs the real governance boundary and implicitly broadens what can override the role.",
      "severity": "major",
      "findings": [
        {
          "id": "f1",
          "severity": "major",
          "description": "The role declares itself 'Subordinate to: docs/v0/architecture.md, docs/VISION.md', which makes static documents part of the operative authority chain instead of treating them as constraints/reference material. That conflicts with the stated controller-governed model and muddies whether the COO/controller or documents are the actual source of authority.",
          "source_section": "<authority>"
        },
        {
          "id": "f2",
          "severity": "major",
          "description": "Using broad strategic docs as direct subordination targets is not scoped tightly enough for a Phase 1 governed builder role and risks silent authority expansion beyond the concrete request/contract boundary.",
          "source_section": "<authority>"
        }
      ],
      "redesign_guidance": "Make the operative authority chain explicit and narrow: report to the COO/controller, treat the approved request plus governed contract as binding inputs, and reference architecture/vision docs only as non-operative constraints or context. Do not list static markdown files as direct superiors."
    },
    {
      "id": "group-2",
      "summary": "The board-review state machine is internally inconsistent, so the package could freeze without a sound approval basis for the current draft version.",
      "severity": "blocking",
      "findings": [
        {
          "id": "f3",
          "severity": "blocking",
          "description": "Step 4 says to 'iterate only with rejecting reviewer', but the guardrails say freeze requires every reviewer to approve. Once the draft changes, prior approvals are stale unless reviewers explicitly re-approve the revised version. The current flow does not define that revalidation.",
          "source_section": "<steps>"
        },
        {
          "id": "f4",
          "severity": "major",
          "description": "The role requires one live Codex leader plus reviewer pairs, but Step 4 does not clearly define whether the leader is a reviewer, an arbiter, or a non-voting executor in the freeze decision. That leaves the authority boundary for final approval underspecified.",
          "source_section": "<role>"
        },
        {
          "id": "f5",
          "severity": "major",
          "description": "Arbitration is mentioned after '2+ consecutive splits', but the draft does not define what arbitration produces, who participates, whether it resets prior approvals, or how it interacts with the 'every reviewer approves' freeze rule.",
          "source_section": "<steps>"
        }
      ],
      "redesign_guidance": "Define review semantics per draft version. Specify who reviews each version, when an approval expires, what the leader can and cannot decide, what arbitration returns, and the exact freeze predicate over the current artifact revision. If any revision occurs, require explicit re-approval from all required participants for that revision."
    },
    {
      "id": "group-3",
      "summary": "The artifact contract is not self-consistent: required outputs, canonical paths, and completion criteria do not line up.",
      "severity": "blocking",
      "findings": [
        {
          "id": "f6",
          "severity": "blocking",
          "description": "The self-check already reports that the required canonical outputs are missing from <outputs>, because the section lists placeholder basenames rather than the required canonical tool-rooted artifact paths.",
          "source_section": "Self-check issues"
        },
        {
          "id": "f7",
          "severity": "major",
          "description": "The contract summary uses basename package file paths like 'agent-role-builder-role.md', while the self-check expects canonical paths under 'tools/agent-role-builder/role/...'. The package path contract is therefore inconsistent within the same draft.",
          "source_section": "Contract summary"
        },
        {
          "id": "f8",
          "severity": "major",
          "description": "Step 5 says the decision log and board summary are always written, but <outputs> marks them as canonical artifacts promoted on freeze, and <completion> only explicitly requires the decision log update on freeze. Non-frozen lifecycle behavior is contradictory.",
          "source_section": "<steps>"
        },
        {
          "id": "f9",
          "severity": "major",
          "description": "The outputs model mixes canonical artifacts, evidence artifacts, and internal run artifacts without a precise statement of where each lives during non-frozen runs versus after promotion. That makes the completion rule 'all applicable artifacts written to output directory' ambiguous.",
          "source_section": "<outputs>"
        }
      ],
      "redesign_guidance": "Adopt one exact artifact contract and use it everywhere. List the canonical promoted paths exactly as required by the tool, separate per-run evidence from promoted canonical artifacts, and make completion criteria terminal-status-specific so frozen, pushback, blocked, and resume_required each have a consistent artifact set."
    }
  ],
  "residual_risks": [
    "The duplicate and near-duplicate exclusions in <scope> make the role harder to maintain and increase the chance of future drift even after the blocking issues are fixed.",
    "The slug-prefix guardrail is still somewhat ambiguous for internal and conditional artifacts such as result and resume packages.",
    "The draft assumes live-provider availability with no provider fallback in runtime config, which may create operational dead-ends even if the package becomes structurally coherent."
  ],
  "strengths": [
    "The draft uses a clear tagged structure and includes the required major sections.",
    "The core guardrails are directionally correct: no invented semantics, no authority expansion, and no freeze with unresolved material pushback.",
    "The role intent and contract summary are aligned at a high level around governed multi-LLM review and frozen packages only after material issues are resolved.",
    "The outputs section usefully distinguishes canonical, evidence, and internal artifacts conceptually, even though the lifecycle details need correction."
  ]
}

